at quickly and\n-safely restores the hair to its\n-natural coloring.. .and it coats\nonly 75c!\nYou can mix it yourself. Just\nblend Sage Tea and Sulphur in\nithe correct proportions. Better,\n<your druggist has it prepared and\nJ ready to use. Ask him for Wyeth\u2019s\n\u25a0>sage Sulphur. Pay him 75c!\nYou Take No Risk\nwe know there is nothing quite\nJso effective as Wynth\u2019s Sage k\nSulphur It brings the result you\n\u2022desire. If you are not more than\nt satisfied, send the empty carton\nito the makers and your money\n:will be refunded. Get Wyeth\u2019s\ni Sage It Sulphur from your drug-\nJf gist.\u2014Advertisement.\nLAWYERS OPPOSE\nj HOOVER DRY PLAN\nChallenge His Right to Advise\nj State Legislatures to En\nact Prohibition Laws.\ni\nBy th* Associated Press.\nNEW YORK. November 13 \u2014The\nj Voluntary Committee of Lawyer*, Inc..\nthrough it* executive committee, in a\ni statement yesterday took issue with\nPresident Hoover's \"assumption that\nStates are under obligation to pass pro\nhlbitlon laws.\" and challenged his right\nto advise State Legislature* as to the\nenactment of any State laws.\nThe statement was issued tn view of j\nreports that dry leaders were preparing\na new State enforcement act to be J\nbrought before the next New York\nLegislature and would use the Presi-\nj denfs inaugural admonition to furthei\ntire prospects of the measure.\nI Composed of Joseph H. Choate. ,Ir..\nchairman; Georg* W. Martin. Kfnneth\nM. Spence, and Harrison Tweed, th*\ni executive committee announced that\nAustin O. Fox. chairman of the Mod- j\neratkm League, had framed the opinions\nadopted.\nMr. Fox\u2019s attack on the reported new\nState enforcement movement,, and the!\nresolution adopted, were centered upon\na statement made before the Legislature\nlast Spring by Assemblyman Edmund\nB. Jenks. sponsor of several dry legis\nlation acts which hare failed to pass In\nthe New York State Legislature.\n\"The of the United States.\"\nMr. Fox told the lawyers\u2019 commits ee,\n\"has no right to lay down any policy\nfor the Legis\u2019ature of New York or any\nother sovereign State. The grant of\npowers to the Executive is limited to\nsuch as the Constitution confers in\nexplicit terms. He has no other powers.\n'H* shall.\u2019 so reads the Constitution.\nKve to the Congress information of\ne state of the Union and recommend\nto their consideration such measures as\nhe shall deem necessary and expedient.'\nThe Constitution contains no mention\nof any power to exercise this function\nwith reference to any legislative body\nexcept to Congreas.\"\n\"In his message of November S, 1929.\nI the President styles himself, quit* cor-\nI rectly. the Chief Magistrate of the Na\ntion.\u201d. the conclusions of Mr. Fox and\nthe committee continue. \"From time to\ntime he has been warning the Nation\nthat acts, even of private individuals,\nthat involve violations of any law tend\nto breed disrespect of all law. What\nshall we say when our Chief Magistrate\nassume* a prerogative not conferred upon\nhim by the Constitution? Not only was\nhis assumption of the right to deter\nmine conclusively the delinquency of\nseveral States a usurpation of power\nnot granted the Executive, and hence\na violation of his oath of office to pre\nserve, protect and defend the Constitu\ntion. but his decision is in flat conflict\nwith the following judicial rulings.\u201d\nThe committee cited opinions of the\nState Supreme Court that \u201cno State is\nrequired to have a prohibitory law-, or\nany law on the subject of intoxicating\nliquor. The State may leave the\nliquor problem to the care of the Fed\neral courts and officers.\u2019\u2019\nWOMAfTSPARTY PAYS\nHONOR TO PIONEER\nDecorate* Statue of Elizabeth Cady\nStanton, Suffrage Leader, an\nHer Birth Anniveraary.\nOfficers of the National Woman's\nParty observed the 114th *nrW\u00bbr\u00bbVY\nof the birth of Elisabeth Cady Stanton,\nequal right* pioneer. In a memorial\nmeeting in the Capitol yesterday morning.\nMrs. Harvey W. Wiley, member of the\nnational council of the Woman\u2019s Party\nand former president of the Elizabeth\nCady Stanton Suffrage Club, paid\ntribute to the mpmory of Mrs. Stanton\nby placing a wreath upon her statue,\nwhich stands In the crypt of the Cap\nitol with the statues of Susan B.\nAnthony and Lucretia Mott.\nMrs. Adelaide Johnson, sculptress of\nthe statue and colleague of Mrs. Stan\nton In the suffrage fight, told of the\nwork that Mrs. Stanton did in gaining\nthe vote for women and in laying the\nprinciples for the National Woman\u2019s\nParty. \"Mrs. Stanton taught the doc\ntrine that equal rights belong to the\nindividual, regardless of sex,\u2019\u2019 Mrs.\nJohnson said.\nMrs. Johnson pointed out that the\nWoman\u2019s Party has embodied this prin\nciple in the equal rights amendment.\nOther members of the Woman\u2019s Party\ndelegation at the memorial meeting\nwere Miss Mabel Vernon of Wilming\nton, Del., national executive secretary\nof the Woman\u2019s Party; Mrs. Dana\nDurand of Washington. D. C.; Miss\nSara Grogan of Georgia; Mrs. Paul\nLinebarger. wife of Judge Llnebarger.\nwho recently returned from China: Mrs.\nHerman Gasch of Washington. D. C.;\ni Miss Louise Wier and Miss Mary Moss\ni Wellborn of Mississippi.\n\nSEES BUSINESS REVIVAL\nI New York Lieutenant Governor\nDiscounts Stock Crash.\nj NEW YORK. November 13 (IP).\u2014\nLieut. Gov. Herbert H. Lehman last\nnight told the New York Credit Men\u2019s\nI Association that he believed business\ni will be affected by the stock market\ndecllpe, but that \u201cthe recovery will be\nmuch faster than any one in the world\nbelieves.\u201d\nThe lieutenant governor is a partner\nin the firm of Lehman Brothers,\nbankers.\n\u201cCheering Stands\u201d\nPush Walker On,\nDeclares Speaker\n\nTammany Held \u201cSnappy\nTeam\u201d and Mayor\n\u201cOpen-Field Runner.\u201d\nBt the Associated Press.\nCHICAGO. November 13. \u2014Mayor\nWalker of New York as a foot ball\nplayer and Tammany Hall as a \"snappy\nfoot ball team\u2019\u2019 was the picture sketch\ned yesterday for the national confer\nence on improving government by\nLuther Gulick, chairman of the Gov\nernmental Research Association.\n\u201cOur bewitching Jimmy,\u201d was, one\nterm Gulick used, mentioning that\nMayor Walker wop last week\u2019s mayor\nalty fight in a \u201cvaudeville election at\nmosphere.\" He continued:\n\u201cin foot ball terms, he Is the great\nest open-field runner I have ever seen.\nHe is quick at picking holes and can\nsliue through the narrowest opening.\nHis change of pace and ability to dodge\nere uncanny. He is a good member of\nthe Tammany team and is proud of the\nyellow persey with the black stripe*.\n\"You will remember that, Walter\nLippman. one of our leading sports\nwriters iLippman\u2019s latest book Is a \u2019A\nPreface to Morals\u2019) told this convention\na few yeu*s ago in Pittsburgh that the\nTammnajy team waa in process of re-\norganization and that a new backfleld\nwas being groomed. There eeems to be\nsome mistake about this. The new stars\nget no support from the team nor from\n1 th* grandstand. Some of them ere\nvery effective now in th* cheering sec\ntion.\u201d\nTHE EVENING STAR. TTASHINGTOy. P. C M WEDNESDAY, NOVEMBER 13, 1929.\nl ..1,, i\nTWO NEW CONGRESSIONAL MEMBERS\nI \u25a0\u25a0\u25a0l I\nHwMijl wa\nft H\nW :M. V 'I\nHI ?s>\u2022\u2022 V Jtopwt, -3<m\nDW, H|f t\nn /w#\nM il\nwm\nJl\nmk Xj\u00df\nSenator R. C. McCulloch of Ohio nnd\nRepresentative Paul J. Kvate of Min\nnesota are the latest additions to the\ncongressional rank* here. Above is\nSrnator McCulloch (right) with Sena\ntor Fess. senior Ohio Senator, shortly\nafter the former assumed his dntir\nyesterday. Representative Kvale (low\ner), who succeeds hi* father, who was\nfatally burned, recently arrived at ihe\nCapitol. \u2014P. &A. Photo\nDISTRICT OPPOSES\nREMOVAL OF TAX\nI\nBill to Relieve S. A. R. Prop\nerty Is Opposed by the\nCommissioners.\nThe District Commissioners yester\nday sent an unfavorable report to Con\ngress on a bill to exempt the property\ni of the National Society of the Son* of\nI the American Revolution from taxation.\nTh- Commissioners pointed out that\nunder the general law exempting prop\nerty used lor educational, charitable\nI and religious purposes, already there is\nj property valued at 175.000,000 on\nwhich no taxes are received.\n\"The Commissioners have had oth*r\nbills referred to them,\u201d the report\nsaid, \u201cproviding for a special law which\nwould increase the present large amount\nof exempt property. Such laws tend\nto shift the burden from taxation from\nthe few directly interested to the gen\neral public.\nSounder Tax Policy.\n\u201cThe Commissioners believe it to be\na sound. fmyJamental policy to insist\nthat the founders and members of\norganisations which are not purely\ncharitable, educational or religious and\ntherefore whose property would not i\nbe exempt under the present general i\nlaw, should pay taxes for such property\nand recognize such an obligation in the\nfounding of their institutions and the\ncalculation of their budgets.\"\nBenefit Fond Opposed.\nThe Commissioners also sent an un\nfavorable report on a bill to appro\npriate 110,000 for Mrs. Jennie Bruce\nGallahan as compensation for the\ndeath of her husband, Lieut. Samuel\nL. Gallahan of the Fire Department.\nLieut. GaUehe.n was killed when the\nhose wagon on which he was riding was\nstruck and overturned by a liquor-laden\ncar on Queens Chapel road northeast\nJuly 35. 1527.\nThe Commiagioiiers pointed out that\nMrs. Gallahan Is receiving the regular 1\npension of S6O a month for her per\nsonal use during widowhood and $lO a\nmonth for a child who Is under the\nage of lg. The Commissioners saw no\nreason why she should receive any spe\ncial consideration.\nARMY ORDERS CHANGE\nSTATIONS OF OFFICERS\nLieut. Col. Pickering Goes to Phil\nippines and Lieut. Col. Brown\nTakes Baltimore Post.\nLieut. Col. Richard R. Pickering.\nAdjutant General\u2019s Department, has been\nrelieved from duty at headquarters.\nThird Corps Area. Baltimore, and or\ndered to the Philippines, end Lteut. Col.\nEdward A. Brown, Adjutant Oeneral\u2019s\nDepartment, now In the Philippines, has\nbeen ordered to Baltimore to relieve\nCol. Pickering; Capt. Joe S. Underwood,\nj Quartermaster Corps, has been trans\nferred from Plattsburg, N. Y\u201e to\nHawaii; Capt. Callie H. Palmer,\nCavalry, from the Philippines to Fort\nMyer, Va.; Capts. Edward M. Fiekett\nand Silas W. Robertson. Cavalry, from\nFort Ringgold. Tex., to the Philippines;\nCapt. Fiank E. Shaw, Judge Advocate\nGeneral\u2019s Department, from the War\nDepartment to Fort Sill, Okla.; Capt.\nAlfred J. Kennedy, Infantry, from Wor\ncester, Mass., to the Philippines, and\nCapt. Guy D. Thompson, Cavalry, from\nFort Riley, Kana., to New York City, for\nduty with the New York National\nGuard.\nThe President has accepted the resig\nnation of Second Lieut. William E.\nThomas. United States Infantry, re\ncently stationed in the Panama \u2018Canal\nZone, to take effect November 20.\nAdmits Slaying Man.\nj PONTIAC, Mich., November 13 (JP).\n\u2014William Mericle, 26, pleaded guilty in\nCircuit Court yesterday to a charge of\nkilling Edward McCrumb, 49. in the base\nment of the latter\u2019s home- last Thurs\nday morning. In a statement to police\nyesterday, Mericle, brought here last\nweek from Dayton, Ohio, said he had\nkilled McCrumb as a \u201cfavor\u201d to his\nfriend, Thomas Delehanty, who is held\nin connection with the slaying.\nPastry Shop\nSANDWICHES\n(ORIGINAL l\nlliivlchci far all anrfal areaitiafii I\nNew location, 806 17th street\nMetropolitan 6939\n45c $3.25'\"'\u201c\nM&gKttfMl laaaaa rtuao\nCalMta _ tm tlmtiil\nDR. CLAUDE S. SEMONES\nEyesight Specialist\nFhona Natlaaal mi\n4M-4IS Mrt.arhlFD Bid,\nlath aeg O St a. N.W.\n4\nl\u00ae*'- I\n\\Hl )0- ms A\u2019JBl\n*1 \u25a0wo \u25a0mf'-\nW\nm j|\nI SF\ni\nt\ni _\nBISHOP FORBIDS\nCOMMUNION PLANS;\nPresbyterian-Officiated Serv\nice Banned in Episcopal\nChurch.\nBy the Associated Press.\nNEW YORK, November 13.\u2014Bishop i\nWilliam T. Manning of the Protestant\nEpiscopal diocese of New York, In a\nletter published today, forbade a com\nmunion service in St. George's Episco\npal Church at which Rev. Dr. James\nSloane Coffin, president of Union The\nological Seminary, was to have offi\nciated.\nThe service was arranged for the close\nI of the New York conference of the\nChristian Unity League which opens\ntoday.\nRev Dr. Karl Reiland, rector of St.\nGeorge's,'loaned the use of his church\nto the Unity League and invited Dr.\ni Coffin to officiate at the communion\nservice neat Friday night.\nIn his letter addressed to Dr. Reiland.\nthe wardens and vestrymen of Bt.\nOeorge's Church, Bishop Manning cited\nthe canons of the Episcopal Church\nand the book of common prayer as for\nbidding any other than Episcopally\nordained ministers from officiating at\nservices in Episcopal Churches. Dr.\nCoffin is a Presbyterian.\nDr. CcTn ma-> public a letter ad- j\ndressed to Dr. Rri\u2019and in whrh h\u00bb said j\nj he had offered the use of the chapel j\nof Union Theological Seminary for the\nI services to Dr. Peter Alnslee of Baltl\nmore, president of the Christian Unity\n1 League\nBishop Manning, in concluding his\nletter forbidding the sen-ice in 6t.\nGeorge\u2019s, said:\nThe members of the Christian Unity\nLeague will not aid the cause of unity\nby trying to override and break down\nthe laws of the churches to wnich they\nGARAGES 11\nIN ALL MATERIALS\ntin Roofs\nPORCHES BUILT\nWE BUILD, REBUILD, REMODEL,\nREPAIR ANYTHING AND GIVE\nTERMS\njTEKVICE\nOrganized 11\nResponsibility I\nU7e\nYellow Cabs\nand\nBlack and White Cabs I\nOwned mnd Operated bp\nBrown Bros.\nI \u2022mmmmmMmmrnm\n\nGo to Eisetnaris Jor\ni SWEATERS\nFor Dress for Sport\nfor Work. Every\nI conceivable style and\nmodel ie represented in\nour great etoek.\n*3 95 to *lO 95\ni EISEMAN\u2019S\n7th F Sts.\nLiniments and exterior applications\nwon\u2019t rid you of the gripping, burn\ning torture of Neuritis. You will have\nto remove the cause before you can\nhope for permanent belief.\nMountain Valley Mineral Water\n..from Hot Springs. Ark., contains\nalkaline* which seem to combat the\nacids or toxins that irritate the\nnerves\u2014lt also stimulates the kidneys\nand aids elimination, which tends to\nrestore health.\nThousands prsise this natural aid\nto relief. Ask your doctor. Phone\ni or write for further Information.\nMetropolitan 1063.\nMountain Valley Water\nI flf Dht. Nstl. Saak Bits.\nNOBEL FOUNDATION\nAWARDS 4PRIZES\nj Five From Foreign Countries\nHonored\u2014U. S. Not In\ncluded in List.\nBy the Associated Preiw.\nSTOCKHOLM. November 13. \u2014The\nNobel Foundation yesterday announced\nfour ewerds, each worth *46,299, and\nfive winners. The prioe in medicine was\nannounced on October 31, so that the\nrmly award for 1929 still unsettled is\nthat for peace, which ia in the hands\nof a Norwegian committee.\nThe award* made today follow;\nLiterature. 1929. Thomas Mann. Ger\nman novelist, who wrote \"Budden\nbrooka\u201d and \"The Magic Mountain.\u201d\nPhysics. 1926, Prof. Owen W. Rirh\nardson of Kings College. London, dis\nroverer of \"Richardson\u2019s law\u201d on the\nmotion of electrons a\u2019hlch forms the\nI basis of the radio tube.\nParisian Is Honored.\nPhysics. 1929. the Due de Broglie of\nParis, a research worker in the fields\nof electricity and the X-ray.\nChemistry. 1929. divided between Dr.\nI Arthur Harden, professor of biochem\nistry at London University, and Prof.\nHans von Euler-Chelpln of Upsaia Uni\nveralty. Sweden, in recognition of their\nresearches in the fermentation of sugars\nand the enzyme action In the process.\nVon Euler-Chelpln is a German who\nha* long been associated with Swedish\nj universities.\nMedicine Prize Split.\nj The medicine prize for 1929 was di-\nided between Dr. Frederick Oowland\nHopkins, professor of biochemistry at i\nIhe University of Cambridge. England,\nand Dr C Eijkmann of the University\nof Utrecht. Holland.\nEnglishmen have thus placed their\ncountry in the forefront by winning one\nfull award and sharing in two others.\n1 The United State*, which has provided\nseveral earlier winners of the Nobel\ni awards, has not taken one since 1927.\nLUNCHEON PAYS HONOR\nTO ECUADOREAN ENVOY\nj By the Associated Press.\nDirector General Rowe of the Pan-\nAmerican Union yesterday entertained a\nI distinguished group of American Gov-\nI eminent officials at a luncheon ui\nj honor of Minister Lafronte of Ecuador.\nBesides Minister Lafronte. the other\nguests included Secretaries Good.\nAdams. Lamont and Davis; Postmaster\nGeneral Brown. Undersecretary Cotton\nof the State Department. American\nAmbassador Culbertson to Chile, who\nreturned to Washington today, and\nRight Rev. Mgr. James H. Ryan, rector\nof Catholic University of America. The\nprincipal members of the etaff of the\nI Ecuadorean legation also attended the\nj affair.\nPeruvian to Head\nDiplomatic Corps\nIn Howard\u2019s Place.\nFor the first time In history, a\nLatin American soon will become\nthe dean of the Washington\ndiplomatic corps. The honor\nwill be accorded to Dr. Heraan\nVelarde, Ambassador of Peru, on\nthe retirement, about the first of\nthe year of Sir Esme Howard,\nAmbassador of Great Britain.\nDr. Velarde will remain In\nWashington until a few days\nafter he becomes the dean.- He\nthen plans to resign. He will be\nsucceeded by Dr. Freyre, Peru\nvian Minister to London.\nJ I\n\nCOAL\nOur low price* are\nfor cash delivery only.\nW. A. EGO $14.60\nW. A. Stove, $15.35\nW. A. Nut. $14.75\nW. A. Pea.. 510.40\nCoke .......$10.75\nFairmont Egg.. $8.35;\nNew River Egg, $ll.OO j\nAlso Buckwheat; soft I\ncoals: fireplace and\nkindling wood. All our\ncoals are screened and\nfull weight guaranteed.\nB. J. WERNER\nDwtriet 6944\n923 New York Ave. N.W.\n1937 Sth St. N.E.\nfti sbtffljtj \u00a7Slaf\nJl^dvertiseneats\ni Ea mma he e I!\nI Smith\u2019s Drug Store\u20147th O Sts. N.W.\nIs a Star Branch Office\nThere\u2019s no other way to so jl\nsuccessfully broadcast any want\nMV that you may have at home or\nin your business as through a\nClassified Advertisement in The\nStar. It's sure to be seen and\nread by practically every one in\nand around Washington.\nLeave copy for The Star I\nH|R Classified Section at the Branch\nrnH Office in your neighborhood. It\n|WK will be promptly forwarded to\nV the Main Office and appear in\nthe first available issue. There\nTHE are no fees for Branch Office\nABOVE BIQN service; only regular rates are\n18 charged.\nDISPLAYED\nBY The Star prints snch an over-\nAUTHORIZED whcltningly greater volume of\ngTA r Classified Advertising every\nbranch ,h ther Was hing\nOPPICEfi ton P*P* r that there can he no\noffices j question as to which will give\nyou the best results.\n\"Around the Corner\u201d is\nm a Star Branch Office\n\u00ab5j v?\nSIR RONALD LINDSAY CHOSEN\nAS BRITAIN'S ENVOY TO U. S.j\nSir Esme Howard to Retire\nNext Year, London For\neign Office Says.\nNew Ambassador Has Had\ni\nTwo Periods of Service,\nat Embassy Here.\nBy the Associated Pres*.\nLONDON. November 18-Sir Ronald\nLindsay. permanent undersecretary of\nstate for foreign affaire, will replace\nSir Esme Howard as British Am\nbassador at Washington early next year.\nAnnouncement of the appointment,\nmade at the British foreign office, said\nSir Esme, whose tenure at the American\npost has extended beyond retirement\nage. would retire with the new Am\nbassador a advent.\ni Sir Robert Venaittart. principa\nprivate secretary to Prime Minister\nRamsay Macdonald. wtll succeed to th*\npost in the foreign ministry vacated by\nSir Ronald.\nSir Robert accompanied Mr. Mac\ni donaid on his American trip and had\nbeen mehtioned prominently in gossip\nax to Sir Esme Howard\u2019s probable\nsuccessor.\nEnvoy to, Raaaia.\nSir Esmond Ovey. recently appointed\nAmbassador to Bradl, had his appoint\nment to that couhtry cancelled, and in\ni stead has been appointed Ambassador\nto Russia, in accordance with recent\nresumption of relations between the\nj Soviet union and Great Brit\u00dfln.\nSir Ronald is 53 years of age. a\nScot, the fifth son of the twenty-sixth j\nearl of Crawfcrd. and a \u201ccareer man\u201d i\n|in the British foreign office. He has\nhad no distinct party affiliations.\nHe served twice at the Washington\nembassy, first from 1905 to 1907, when\nLord Bryce was Ambassador and Theo\ndore Roosevelt President of the United\nStates, and later In 1919 and 1930\nwhen he was counselor at the embassy\nduring President Wilson\u2019s fight for\nAmerican entry into the League of\nNations.\nMarried t* New Yorker.\nHe was married in 1924 to Elisabeth\nSherman Hoyt, daughter of the late j\nColgate Hoyt of New York. His first\nwife also wax an American sernsn.\nMartha Cameron, daughter of former\nSenator J. Donald Cameron of Penn\nsylvania. She died In 1918.\nSir Ronald once was Ambassador to\nTurkey and again Ambassador at Ber\nlin. He also served at St. Petersburg, i\nTeheran, Parte. The Hague and in\nEgypt. He became permanent under-\nsecretary in the foreign ministry in\n1928.\nHe is a most poptflar figure in Great 1\nBritain.\nVIEWED AS COMPLIMENT.\ni By the Associated Press.\nAppointment of Sir Ronald Lindsay\njto succeed Ambassador Howard was\nviewed in high administration and i\n1\nUnder 7 5* pervision\nU. S. Treasury\nJThis Bank has made\nover 38 thousand loans\naggregating nearly 9\nmillions of dollars to as\nsist persons of character\nto accomplish some\nworthy purpose.\nJin connection with the\nloan the borrower agrees\nto make monthly# or\nsemi-monthly deposits\nin a savings account\n'with which he may\npay the loan; thus the\nborrower forms the\nhabit of saving regu\nlarly.\nA\nWHL. Q\u00bb v\nH 1 Jfl\nVj iJA\nSIR RONALD LINDSAY.\n\u2014Henry Miller Photo. 1\ndiplomatic circles today as a compli- j\nment to the United States Oovemment, j\nevidencing the importance the Labor,\ngovernment attaches to Anglo-American\nj relations.\nAs undersecretary of s*ate for foreign\naffairs he had active charge of the Brit-\nj ish foreign office. The name of Sir\nI Ronald has been well known in Wash\nington for a number of years, numerous\nfriends hat ing been made by him while\nattached to the embassy here.\nSecretary Stimson was not available\nfor comment last night, having planned\na hunting trip in Virginia.\nPresident Hoover Is expected to re\nceive Sir Ronald\u2019s credentials In Febru\nary, at which time Sir Esme Howard\nwill retire from the British foreign\nservice.'\nSir Esme has held the ambassadorship\nhere since March 5, 1924, and is dean\nof the diplomatic corps. Ambassador\nHernan Velarde of Peru, who took his\npost 20 days after Bir Esme arrived,\nwill become dean of the corps.\nRevolving Stadium Idea.\nPRINCETON. N. J.. November 13\n\u2014A great boon to alumni and other\nfoot, ball nuts seems possible. A con\ntributor to the Princeton Alumni Week\nlv has a simple method by which every\nbody at a game can have as good a\n1 seat as anybody else. It Is to build a\nstadium on a track and have it revolve\nduring the game.\nRelax and Enjoy\nA cup of delicious SALADA\nwill quickly renew your\nenergy any time you\nfeel tired.\n\"SALADA\"\nTEA\n\u201cFresh from the Qardens\u201d sn\nNO MEDICAL EXAMINATION! N* S\u00abbfcrif\u00bbtion Necessary\nrt coupon below raibiM readers ot the Policies Sent by M ail!\nWashlntton Btmr to apply for Standard\nEndowment Insurance with extra\nbenefits\u2014at very low coat- and to pay tor v&aPfl\u00dfplElHyiifin\nIt cm e\u00abs\u00bb oios ffif* savmentt.\nNO MEDICAL EXAMINATION IS RE- Mk\nQCIRFD! No subscription is nfcusu Send tjjSf IHBs-:; Mam fcal\nthe coupon below. Policies are sent by mail.\nThis ofler is open to men, women and children. BMMBI I\nin normal health, between the asm o< 10 and SO. Kgjfe \u25a0\u25a0\u25a0?\"\u2019\u2019i|k\u00abrfttaSiSSfe r:\nIf yoo are not m normal health or me not a ta